<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,465,332,357]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
Large species, very convex and with oval body form (
<figureCitation box="[1114,1199,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 11" captionStartId="10.[151,260,1724,1747]" captionTargetBox="[246,1348,305,1664]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[204,1382,267,1703]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 11. Dorsal and lateral habitus views of holotypes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/288369/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[1170,1199,332,356]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
), pronotal disc nonmicroreticulate, elytra very weakly microreticulate. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[858,939,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 22" captionStartId="13.[151,260,1761,1784]" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 22. Aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="14" pageNumber="55">
Fig. 
<number box="[910,939,368,392]" pageId="14" pageNumber="55" value="22.0">22</number>
</figureCitation>
) large and robust, base slightly widened and housing internal capsule; distal part with setae as illustrated; apex with oval lobe, wrinkled on surface, and emerging from this a rigid, arcuate, tube-like internal duct, apparently permanently everted.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
